      "id": 359216,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>The p<i>K</i><sub>a</sub>’s of five <i>p</i>-substituted benzoic acids (<span class=\"magenta-text\">Y</span>C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>4</sub>CO<sub>2</sub>H) are listed below. Rank the corresponding substituted benzenes (<span class=\"magenta-text\">Y</span>C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>) in order of their increasing reactivity toward electrophilic aromatic substitution. If benzoic acid has p<i>K</i><sub>a</sub> = 4.19, which of the substituents are activators and which are deactivators?</p>\n<table summary=\"\" class=\"unnumbered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th><b>Substituent Y</b></th>\n<th><img src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBdDhXIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--459666c623c6e7ed73c2563d856ebf51353ab76e/OChem_20_EC_033.jpg\" alt=\"The structure of benzoic acid with a substituent Y placed para to the carboxylic acid group attached to the benzene ring. To the left, p k a term is mentioned.\"></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–Si(CH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub></td>\n<td>4.27</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–CH═CHC≡N</td>\n<td>4.03</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–HgCH<sub>3</sub></td>\n<td>4.10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–OSO<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>3</sub></td>\n<td>3.84</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>–PCl<sub>2</sub></td>\n<td>3.59</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>",
